"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830752?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">埃隆·马斯克在 X（更名为 Twitter）上的一篇帖子中透露了他可能进行的手术。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：alain jocard/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001115210"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/will-feuer" itemprop="url" rel="author">威尔·福尔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 7 日上午 7:51 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-surgery-mark-zuckerberg-fight-3598da84"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">特斯拉</a>首席执行官<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">埃隆·马斯克</a>表示，他将于周一对颈部和上背部进行核磁共振检查，并表示在与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta</a>首席执行官<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">马克·扎克伯格</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/sports/mark-zuckerberg-elon-musk-fight-cage-match-7b28d9c1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">进行笼式比赛</a>之前，他可能需要接受手术。</p><p>这两位科技亿万富翁互相吐槽，52 岁的马斯克周日表示，这场比赛将在 X（更名为 Twitter）上进行直播，收益将捐献给退伍军人慈善机构。</p><p>扎克伯格周日在 Threads 上发帖称，他建议 8 月 26 日举行比赛，但仍在等待确认。 “我今天已经准备好了，”他说。 “没有屏住呼吸。”</p><p>马斯克和扎克伯格的预期对峙凸显了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-mark-zuckerberg-cage-fight-b71fa4ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">科技亿万富翁之间长达数年的竞争</a>，在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-rapid-rise-of-threads-appears-to-be-hurting-twitter-f557ba6e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">扎克伯格推出 Threads</a>直接与马斯克的 X Corp 竞争后，这场竞争达到了紧要关头。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=C88AF8C6-9381-4531-8397-8E3466D42127&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Felon-musk-surgery-mark-zuckerberg-fight-3598da84&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Twitter 所有者埃隆·马斯克 (Elon Musk) 和 Meta 首席执行官马克·扎克伯格 (Mark Zuckerberg) 已同意进行笼式比赛。肢体冲突可能是第一次，但《华尔街日报》的乔安娜·斯特恩在动作玩偶的帮助下解释了为什么这场科技斗殴实际上就像过去的硅谷争吵一样。照片插图：Kenny Wassus、Preston Jessee<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>马斯克在 X 上的一篇帖子中披露了可能进行的手术。马斯克是世界首富，同时也是 SpaceX 的首席执行官。</p><p>周一盘前交易中，特斯拉股价上涨约 0.3%，至 254.60 美元。</p><p>马斯克长期以来一直<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-is-all-about-the-nonstop-grind-and-he-cant-stop-talking-about-it-551d2abd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在讨论他艰苦的工作时间</a>，并表示他的日程安排影响了他的睡眠。他还表示自己<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-does-elon-musk-sleep-billionaire-speaks-of-limits-to-fixing-twitter-and-his-back-pain-11675604800?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">患有“相当严重的背痛”。</a></p><p>马斯克上个月表示，他“可能需要进行手术来加固将我的 C5/C6 椎骨固定在一起的钛板。”</p><p> MRI 是一种无创医学成像测试，可生成身体内部结构的详细图像。</p><p>写信给 Will Feuer： <a href="mailto:Will.Feuer@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Will.Feuer@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 11:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-surgery-mark-zuckerberg-fight-3598da84</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-surgery-mark-zuckerberg-fight-3598da84<author><![CDATA[Will Feuer]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台/工具</category><category>技术</category><category>管理</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>高层管理人员</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>特斯拉</category><category>马克·扎克伯格</category><category>埃隆·马斯克</category><category>管理</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>高层管理人员</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category><category>社交媒体平台</category><category>工具</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[AI Set to Upend the Talent Search at Ad Agencies and Brands]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>生成式人工智能可以帮助招聘人员找到更多样化、更专业的候选人，但求职者也用它来润色自己的简历<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001111748"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830228?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一屏 ChatGPT 回复。招聘人员表示，生成式人工智能可以增强雇主为特定工作寻找最佳候选人的能力。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Jaap Arriens/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001111748"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/patrick-coffee" itemprop="url" rel="author">帕特里克·咖啡</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 7 日上午 6:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-set-to-upend-the-talent-search-at-ad-agencies-and-brands-cf9df34f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>正如生成式人工智能似乎即将<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-advertising-industry-tools-risks-f880420a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">改变营销人员的日常工作</a>一样，它也可能会颠覆招聘人员的工作，以找到合适的人选。</p><p>招聘人员表示，这项技术一方面可以帮助品牌和广告公司更有效地确定求职目标，但另一方面，它将使简历的分类变得更加困难，因为更多的简历本身就是人工智能的产品。</p><p>二十多年来，招聘人员一直在使用所谓的机器学习人工智能，主要以软件的形式使用职位描述来自动过滤申请人库。然而，招聘人员认为，生成式人工智能的出现将增强他们为特定工作寻找最佳候选人的能力。</p><p>广告控股公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WPP" class="">WPP</a>人才招聘和猎头全球主管 Shannon Moorman 表示：“我已经这样做很长时间了，这可能是我见过的最关键的、会扰乱招聘的事情<span class="company-name-type">。</span> ”</p><p>摩尔曼说，人工智能对营销组织特别有帮助，这些组织经常进行复杂的搜索，旨在预测候选人的未来表现以及他们的直接经验。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="426" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830250?width=639&amp;height=426" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Bard，谷歌的人工智能入口。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Nikos Pekiaridis/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> ChatGPT 和 Google 的 Bard 等工具最直接的用途在于自动化部分重复性任务：向候选人写直接消息并创建职位列表大纲。在这两种情况下，人工智能生成的内容都可以由人类定制，以更好地描述营销人员越来越寻求的高度专业化和以技术为中心的角色。</p><p>广告公司 Goodby Silverstein &amp; Partners 的副合伙人兼人才总监扎克·坎菲尔德 (Zach Canfield) 表示，ChatGPT“可能会为你提供 40% 的大纲，然后你必须对其进行真正的微调”。坎菲尔德表示，生成式人工智能带来的效率提升为该机构腾出了更多时间来寻找和瞄准创意专业人士，例如那些在人工智能、虚拟现实和相关技术方面拥有经验的人。</p><p>营销人员经常寻找国际候选人来担任顶级创意职位。对于他们来说，生成式人工智能可以总结美国移民法所需的复杂法律文件，并帮助招聘人员与这些候选人更流畅地沟通。</p><p> “对于候选人来说，这是一条双向路。有时我的西班牙语比他们的英语强，所以我确实相信 [AI] 会带来一些安慰和可信度，并在双方之间建立融洽的关系，”经常使用 Bard 和其他人工智能工具的创意招聘公司 Sasha the Mensch 总裁 Sasha Martens 说道。例如翻译 DeepL，在美国境外招聘时更确定地使用当地俚语</p><h3>弹奏弦乐</h3><p>然而，生成式人工智能对营销招聘人员最引人注目的用途可能在于它能够简化流程，例如创建所谓的布尔字符串，这是一系列“如果、那么和”提示，用于更准确地定位候选人，莫尔曼说。</p><p> Moorman 表示，过去，WPP 招聘人员可能会花费数小时编写数百个字符串，以便在湾区寻找具有 JavaScript 编码语言专业知识的软件开发人员。现在，生成式人工智能已经自动化了大部分工作，创建布尔字符串来找到符合招聘人员目标的候选人，有时会建议招聘人员没有明确要求的更精确的目标关键词。</p><p>莫尔曼说，招聘人员还可以利用人工智能从现有的职位描述中提取一组关键词，使用这些术语创建一个新的字符串并进一步细化搜索结果。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Moorman 表示，当与 HireEZ 等机器学习工具相结合时，生成式人工智能可以打开搜索范围，包括 Reddit 子社区、开发者论坛和历史悠久的黑人学院和大学的校友团体等在线圈子。她说，WPP 这样就可以更快地从更广泛的候选人群体中进行选拔。</p><p> “人工智能让我兴奋的一件事是，它实际上将为我们打开多样化人才库的大门，否则我们甚至不会意识到这一点，”莫尔曼说。</p><p>她说，如果使用得当，生成人工智能还可以减少偏见，例如帮助识别职位描述中可能会阻止女性申请的男性倾向术语。 （WPP 发言人表示，其中包括“驱动”、“客观”和“坚定”。）剔除此类线索的能力对于那些经常难以实现自身多元化招聘目标的营销组织来说可能很有用。</p><p>坎菲尔德说，富有创意的招聘人员根据候选人工作的公认质量（而不是他们的技术专长）进行搜索，也可能会发现人工智能对于研究目的很有价值。例如，如果 Goodby Silverstein &amp; Partners 想要瞄准近年来最受欢迎的汽车品牌活动背后的思想家，招聘人员可以使用 ChatGPT 提示来收集在行业颁奖典礼上名列前茅的更全面的工作清单，包括他们的例子他说，可能已经忘记或以前没有见过。</p><p>人工智能“并没有改变我的申请者工作流程，但它改变了我的能力，让我能够更好地主动寻找那些我想主动追求的人，”坎菲尔德说。</p><h3><strong>准确性尚未保证</strong></h3><p>但麦肯锡合伙人布莱恩·汉考克表示，人工智能加速招聘的最大障碍仍然是其制造虚假信息的倾向。</p><p>汉考克说：“当你在做背景调查或准备面试时，它可能会对候选人产生一些影响。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="426" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830254?width=639&amp;height=426" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> LinkedIn 今年开始为用户提供人工智能工具，让他们的简历更受欢迎。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Jaap Arriens/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>例如，当汉考克要求一个所谓的大型语言模型工具来总结他自己的传记时，它告诉他，他毕业于康奈尔大学工业与劳动关系学院；事实上，他就读于弗吉尼亚大学。</p><p>招聘公司 CPS 的高级合伙人兼 AI 创始人 David J. Schueneman 表示，许多高管招聘人员尚未完全接受人工智能，但他们面临着来自已经接受人工智能的竞争对手的压力，以及越来越多渴望向他们出售相关产品的供应商的压力。其营销专业部门ad+one。</p><p>具有讽刺意味的是，所有这些自动化意味着招聘人员正在尝到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-isnt-coming-for-marketers-jobsnot-yet-at-least-3bc18750?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一些营销专业人士已经感受到的</a>对工作保障的焦虑。舒内曼表示，这种担忧与二十年前 LinkedIn 等在线求职论坛和平台的兴起所引起的恐慌相呼应。</p><p>他说，这些担忧可能是没有根据的，因为招聘最终依赖于人与人之间的互动。他说，随着人工智能变得越来越流行，进而变得更加商品化，它对招聘人员的竞争优势将会消失，因为“人工智能驱动”等短语的无处不在使得它们几乎毫无意义。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您认为人工智能技术将如何改变招聘流程？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>求职者自己对人工智能工具包的了解使招聘人员的流程进一步复杂化，在某些方面加强了人工密切关注的必要性。</p><p>一些人工智能工具，比如 LinkedIn 今年发布的工具，是专门为帮助申请人填写个人资料而设计的。全球招聘网络 (Global Recruiters Network) 的业务开发经理约翰·罗腾堡 (John Rothenburg) 表示，它们的受欢迎程度意味着招聘人员现在面临着大量类似的简历，其中充满了所有最热门的关键词。全球招聘网络是一家将求职者与各行业公司联系起来的公司。</p><p> “突然之间，每个候选人都成为了一名优秀的作家，”罗腾堡说。 “他们将自己定位为 A 级玩家，但实际上他们是 B 级玩家或 C 级玩家。”</p><p> “我们的招聘人员需要整理更多的噪音，”他说。</p><p>写信给 Patrick Coffee <a href="mailto:patrick.coffee@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">patrick.coffee@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-set-to-upend-the-talent-search-at-ad-agcies-and-brands-cf9df34f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-set-to-upend-the-talent-search-at-ad-agcies-and-brands-cf9df34f<author><![CDATA[Patrick Coffee]]></author><category>人工智能技术</category><category>广告服务</category><category>广告/营销/公共关系</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>营销服务</category><category>技术</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>职业规划/管理</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>求职</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>职业生涯规划</category><category>管理</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>一般劳工问题</category><category>求职</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category><category>人工智能技术</category><category>广告服务</category><category>广告</category><category>营销</category><category>公共关系</category><category>商业</category><category>消费服务</category><category>营销服务</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Real-Estate Haven Turns Perilous With $1 Trillion Coming Due]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>公寓楼的价值多年来一直上涨，但飙升的利率现在笼罩着该行业的业主<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830485/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="随着租金稳步上涨，投资者抬高了多户住宅的价格。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>随着租金稳步上涨，投资者抬高了多户住宅的价格。理查德·B·莱文/祖玛出版社<span>理查德·B·莱文/祖玛出版社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001112088"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001112088"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/konrad-putzier" itemprop="url" rel="author">康拉德·普齐尔</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/will-parker" itemprop="url" rel="author">威尔·帕克</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 7 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>长期以来被认为是房地产天堂的公寓楼正在成为陷入困境的商业地产领域的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/houston-apartment-owner-loses-3-200-units-to-foreclosure-as-multifamily-feels-the-heat-fb3d0e75?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">下一个主要麻烦点</a>。</p><p>多年来，受租金稳步上涨和巨额回报前景的吸引，投资者不断抬高多户住宅的价格。许多人承担了过多的债务，期望能够以足够快的速度提高租金来偿还债务。</p><p>与受到远程工作和电子商务严重打击的写字楼和商场不同，出租公寓的空置率较低。公寓行业的主要问题不是缺乏需求——自 2020 年以来租金飙升——而是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investors-bet-that-high-rates-will-linger-61cdaeb7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">利率</a>。</p><p>去年债务成本的突然飙升现在有可能使全国许多多户家庭业主破产。数据公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CSGP" class="">CoStar</a>的数据显示，继去年上涨 25% 后，截至 6 月份的一年中，公寓楼价值下降了 14% <span class="company-name-type">。</span>这一下降幅度与写字楼价值的下降幅度大致相同。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830530?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">许多公寓楼投资者承担了过多的债务，期望他们能够足够快地提高租金来偿还债务。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：大卫·保罗·莫里斯/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>多户住宅类别的抵押贷款拖欠率较低，但仍在增加。借贷成本翻了一番，租金增长放缓，建筑费用上升。数据提供商特雷普今年早些时候发现，在面临违约风险的商业抵押贷款中，一类出租公寓债务占很大比例。</p><p>资深房地产金融高管、黑石房地产债务业务创始成员彼得·索托洛夫 (Peter Sotoloff) 表示，公寓业主面临着“氢弹情景”。<br><br>根据抵押贷款银行家协会的数据，未偿还的多户抵押贷款在过去十年中增加了一倍多，达到约 2 万亿美元。特雷普表示，这几乎是办公室债务的两倍。该数据提供商补充说，9807 亿美元的多户家庭债务预计将在 2023 年至 2027 年间到期。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830785?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “每个人都专注于办公室，”索托洛夫说。他补充说，公寓违约的风险“是一个非常大的问题，但没有得到应有的关注。”</p><p>洛杉矶、休斯顿和旧金山的多户住宅业主拖欠了数千套公寓的贷款。据一位知情人士透露<span class="company-name-type">，</span>全球最大的另类资产管理公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BX" class="">Blackstone</a>已拖欠曼哈顿 11 栋公寓楼的抵押贷款。 Blackstone 的一位发言人表示，这些建筑存在独特的问题，“不能代表我们在更广泛的租赁住房组合中看到的实力。”</p><p>公寓楼被誉为风险较低的商业房地产投资。即使在经济衰退时期，包括2008-2009年金融危机期间房地产市场崩溃时，它们的表现也相对较好。人们总是需要一个地方居住，在危机时期，前房主会涌入租赁市场。</p><p>通货膨胀还使房东能够比平时提高租金，从而推高了其建筑物的价值。根据租赁网站 Apartment List 的数据，2021 年至 2022 年 18 个月内，租金要价上涨了 25%。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">由于住房供应短缺，开发商正在将更多空置办公室改造成公寓。但并非所有建筑物都适合重复利用，尽管美国各地有超过 10 亿平方英尺的办公空间闲置 图片插图：Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>对于许多投资者来说，这些因素<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rising-interest-rates-concern-apartment-building-owners-renters-11653393600?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">证明支付高价是合理的</a>。公寓楼业主通常从债券市场借入超过 80% 的建筑价值。大多数公寓贷款都是固定利率的长期抵押贷款。然而，在疫情期间，投资者获得了更多<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bonds-backed-by-apartments-are-under-stress-as-housing-market-cools-9717d617?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">短期浮动利率贷款</a>。</p><p>许多投资者大幅提高租金，押注一旦他们的建筑物产生更高的租金收入，他们就可以以更高的估值出售建筑物或为债务再融资。</p><p>但很少有人预料到利率会上升得如此之快，从而压低建筑价值并迫使房东以更高的利率进行再融资。作为重要资金来源的地区性银行如今的放贷量大幅减少，导致抵押贷款再融资变得更加困难。美国许多城市<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/renters-are-about-to-get-the-upper-hand-f6387df4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的租金增长大幅放缓</a><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/renters-are-about-to-get-the-upper-hand-f6387df4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，</a>而通货膨胀和保险费上涨则提高了建筑物的运营成本。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830093?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>主要由浮动利率债务和小投资者现金资助的一批新的私人房地产公司已成为多户住宅市场上更大的竞争对手。一些人基于对未来几年租金大幅上涨的乐观预期而支付了更高的价格。现在，他们在使数字发挥作用方面遇到了困难。</p><p>总部位于洛杉矶的 Tides Equities 自 2016 年以来已收购了价值超过 65 亿美元的租赁房产，其中大部分是西南部城市的中低收入公寓楼。评级机构报告显示，2021 年，该公司预计达拉斯郊区的一处房产的租金将在三年内上涨 44%。<br><br> 6 月，Tides 告诉投资者，该战略并未按计划进行。该公司在一封信中表示，租户“现金变得过于紧张”。信中称，一些房产不再赚取足够的钱来偿还债务，投资者可能需要投入更多资金来挽救建筑物免于违约。</p><p> Tides 联合创始人 Sean Kia 和 Ryan Andrade 在接受采访时表示，他们正在与贷方合作，寻找避免面临困难的房产违约的方法。</p><p>总部位于休斯敦的 Nitya Capital 拥有价值约 30 亿美元的多户住宅，该公司在 3 月份通知投资者，由于利率上升，该公司将大幅削减利润预期。</p><p> Nitya 首席执行官 Swapnil Agarwal 在一封投资者信中写道：“我们实际上是在支付更高的抵押贷款成本，而不是进行现金分配。”</p><p>公寓业主仍有理由保持乐观。即使银行撤退，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FNMA" class="company-name">房利美</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/FMCC" class="company-name">房地美</a>仍能提供政府支持的可靠贷款来源。大多数分析师预计住房短缺和高租金将持续存在。如果利率下降，房地产价格可能会迅速反弹。拥有固定利率抵押贷款的多户家庭业主更有能力度过任何近期的动荡。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您对商业地产的前景如何？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>尽管如此，其他威胁仍在加剧。今年和明年开业的新公寓楼数量异常多，特别是在高端租赁市场，引起了供应方面的担忧。</p><p> CoStar资本市场分析全国总监查德·利特尔(Chad Littell)表示，此外，公寓楼价值比商业楼宇价值更容易受到利率上涨的影响，因为它们与10年期国债价格密切相关，而随着利率上升，十年期国债价格暴跌。</p><p>即使是一些经历过风暴的资深房地产投资者也显得很脆弱。旧金山最大的房东之一<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NZ/XNZE/GSH" class="">Veritas Investments</a><span class="company-name-type">及其</span>合作伙伴在过去一年中拖欠了 95 栋出租建筑的债务。结果，该公司将损失超过三分之一的旧金山投资组合。</p><p>该公司今年早些时候表示，“多户型房地产行业正面临着许多与其他资产类别（包括办公楼、零售业和酒店业）相同的财务挑战。”</p><p>写信给 Konrad Putzier <a href="mailto:konrad.putzier@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（konrad.putzier@wsj.com）</a>和 Will Parker（ <a href="mailto:will.parker@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">will.parker@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528<author><![CDATA[Konrad PutzierWill Parker]]></author><category>住房</category><category>商业地产</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>住房</category><category>商业房地产</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>黑色的石头</category><category>巴克斯</category><category>房利美</category><category>国家气象局</category><category>房地美</category><category>FMCC</category><category>科星集团</category><category>CSGP</category><category>良好的精神好客</category><category>谷胱甘肽新西兰</category><category>新西兰：还原型谷胱甘肽</category><category>彼得·索托洛夫</category><category>肖恩·基亚</category><category>瑞安·安德拉德</category><category>斯瓦普尼尔·阿加瓦尔</category><category>查德·利特尔</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Hell of Living In a Home With Any Celebrity Connection]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>走开，格雷斯兰。多亏了社交媒体和谷歌地图，即使是不太出名的房子现在也会吸引大量的游客——一些业主会从中得到乐趣。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828333/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="曼哈顿科妮莉亚街的一栋泰勒·斯威夫特曾经居住过的房子吸引了很多想要拍照的人。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>曼哈顿科妮莉亚街的一栋泰勒·斯威夫特曾经居住过的房子吸引了很多想要拍照的人。詹妮弗·克里根/华尔街日报<span>詹妮弗·克里根/华尔街日报</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093607"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093607"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/candace-taylor" itemprop="url" rel="author">坎迪斯·泰勒</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 7 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/celebrity-houses-famous-homes-6ba91102"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>纽约——周二晚上，曼哈顿西村的一条小街科妮莉亚街。下午 6 点刚过，17 岁的莉莉·波斯纳 (Lily Posner) 和她的祖母在街上漫步，在大约半个街区的地方停了下来。在那里，他们开始拍摄砖房的照片。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          twocolumn
"><figure class="media-object-image img-twocolumn"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="140" height="61" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830826?width=140&amp;height=61" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><p>身穿灰色连帽衫、拎着购物袋的波斯纳解释说，她是泰勒·斯威夫特的“超级粉丝”，泰勒·斯威夫特在 2016 年左右租下了这栋房子，并在她的歌曲《科妮莉亚街》中将它永垂不朽。波斯纳是佛蒙特州居民，他花了一天的时间购物和观光，然后停下来参观斯威夫特以前的住所。</p><p>尽管这位歌手从未拥有过这所房子并且只在那里住过很短一段时间，但波斯纳的热情丝毫没有减弱。她称参观科妮莉亚街是他们旅行的一大亮点。 “我喜欢这首歌，”她说。 “这是标志性的。”当她说话时，另一对粉丝来到家里拍照。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="944" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828344?width=700&amp;height=944" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">莉莉·波斯纳在泰勒·斯威夫特以前的公寓</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：莉莉·波斯纳</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>几个街区之外，佩里街 66 号 (66 Perry Street) 前也上演着类似的场景，这是一座褐砂石建筑，曾是电视剧《欲望都市》中凯莉·布拉德肖 (Carrie Bradshaw) 的家。别介意该系列于 2004 年结束：每隔几分钟，就有一群人沿着绿树成荫的街道蜿蜒前行，为这座房子拍照。门廊上挂着一条链子，上面挂着“私人财产：禁止侵入”的牌子，并附有小声喧哗和远离台阶的指示。</p><p>退到一边，格雷斯兰。如今，一处住宅不一定要特别出名才能吸引源源不断的好奇——有时甚至是咄咄逼人的——访客。多亏了社交媒体和谷歌地图，即使是不太出名的家庭现在也可能挤满了渴望自拍或重温屏幕时刻的人们。这可能会让房主感到惊讶，他们发现自己正在处理旅游请求或无意中听到即兴唱歌。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830980?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">马克吐温去世的房子的主人说，前来参观的游客数量稳步增加。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：航拍 360 度解决方案</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“现在，因为一切都在网上，任何有兴趣的人都可以在大约五分钟内找到它的确切位置，”埃里卡·德·桑蒂斯说，她是康涅狄格州雷丁市马克·吐温去世的房子的所有者。她说，近年来，来她家看望的所谓“吐温尼亚人”的数量稳步增加。</p><p>在新墨西哥州阿尔伯克基，《绝命毒师》中沃尔特·怀特的家所在的房子的主人在粉丝不断向屋顶扔披萨后，在房子周围竖起了栅栏，以向剧中的一个关键场景致敬。当指南针房地产经纪人拉里萨·彼得罗维奇（Larissa Petrovic）最近向潜在买家展示斯威夫特位于科妮莉亚街（Cornelia Street）的住宅时，她说他们对拍摄它的人数感到震惊。他们没有提出报价。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="394" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816018?width=700&amp;height=394" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 《绝命毒师》中的一个场景是在新墨西哥州一户人家的屋顶上吃披萨。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：AMC</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>康帕斯 (Compass) 的房地产经纪人丹尼·布朗 (Danny Brown) 列出了洛杉矶房屋的清单，该房屋是《布雷迪家族》(The Brady Bunch) 中房屋的外观。他的客户 HGTV 对室内装饰进行了翻新，以配合情景喜剧的布景，并于 5 月以 550 万美元的价格投放市场。 “这真是太疯狂了，不断有放映请求，”布朗说。大多数都不是来自认真的买家，而是人们只是想看看里面。布朗说，最近，潜在买家穿着“十足的 70 年代复古服装”来到这里。当他们参观房子时，两名妇女在外面站了 20 分钟，唱着节目的主题曲。潜在买家走到外面参加小夜曲。 “这是五六个人合唱的主题曲，”布朗说。 “这就是发生在这所房子前面的那种疯狂的事情。”</p><p>他说，这栋房子现已签订合同，并将在几周内关闭。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/fc5d16f6-3f02-4ee9-add8-6a35b8286fcc.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> 2017 年，约翰·塔什吉安 (John Tashjian) 和凯蒂·塔什吉安 (Katie Tashjian) 买下了南卡罗来纳州的房子，这里是 80 年代电影《大寒》的拍摄地。房地产开发商约翰·塔什吉安 (John Tashjian) 表示，当他们买下这栋 1850 年代左右的房子时，它年久失修，里面还保留着电影拍摄时的两套布景。这对夫妇在搬入全职住所之前进行了为期三年的装修。</p><p>该住宅是当地的地标。尽管如此，他们还是对游客的数量和坚持感到惊讶。约翰·塔什吉安 (John Tashjian) 表示，每个工作日大约有 25 至 50 人前来拜访，周末的人数是这个数字的两倍。除了拍照之外，许多人还高唱《The Big Chill》中的歌曲，尤其是三只狗之夜的《Joy to the World》。</p><p> “我无法告诉你有多少次我听到人们唱‘耶利米是一只牛蛙’，就像这是某种旧时代的复兴一样，”他说。</p><p>当他们第一次搬进来时，他们把房子的大门开着。然而，太多人冒险进入他们的院子，以至于他们最终安装了自动关闭的大门。 “有人坐在我们的院子里拍视频，”约翰·塔什吉安 (John Tashjian) 说。其他人带来了野餐或重现了电影中的场景。有些人敲门要求参观。有时他会答应，这取决于“我当时的心情”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="839" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828350?width=1260&amp;height=839" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">凯蒂和约翰·塔什吉安在南卡罗来纳州的家中。这座房子是电影《大寒》中的取景地，吸引了许多游客。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：夏洛特·伯克利</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="470" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829803?width=700&amp;height=470" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 1983 年，《大寒》的演员包括格伦·克洛斯、凯文·克莱恩、梅格·蒂莉、威廉·赫特、汤姆·贝伦杰、玛丽·凯·普莱斯、杰夫·高布伦和乔贝斯·威廉姆斯。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：埃弗里特收藏</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他说，如今，游客可以在门外拍照。当那些看起来很丑的人在草地上开车，或者撞倒庄园边缘的钢柱时，他确实会感到恼火。尽管如此，他意识到关注度是随着领土而来的。 “如果你打算拥有这所房子，你不会对这里的接待感到惊讶，”他说。 “这就像住在机场旁边并抱怨飞机一样。”</p><p>这些家庭越来越受到关注的原因之一是流媒体服务使旧电视和电影可以立即观看。</p><p> 2012 年，房地产经纪人阿黛尔·柯蒂斯 (Adele Curtis) 代表了伊利诺伊州温内特卡 (Winnetka) 房屋的买家，该房屋是 1990 年电影《小鬼当家》的拍摄地。 “那时，一切都很平淡，这就是‘小鬼当家’的房子，”她说。在乔治亚砖砌店里，她从未注意到路人在拍照。</p><p>如今，“无论白天还是晚上的任何时间”，都可以看到粉丝们在屋外拍照，她说。 “它变得比以往任何时候都更受欢迎。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816038?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">粉丝们在伊利诺伊州温内特卡的电影《小鬼当家》中的房子外拍照。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Youngrae Kim/华盛顿邮报/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="474" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830846?width=700&amp;height=474" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 1990 年的《小鬼当家》中的麦考利·卡尔金。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：20 世纪福克斯/埃弗雷特收藏</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>詹姆斯·C·巴里 (James C. Barry) 的父母是《黄金女郎》中布兰奇 (Blanche)、多萝西 (Dorothy)、罗丝 (Rose) 和索菲亚 (Sophia) 所住房屋的长期业主。 ，一名男子敲门说他的女朋友是该节目的超级粉丝，并询问他是否可以在家门口的车道上向她求婚。巴里的母亲同意了，在他提出求婚后，“她端着香槟出来给他们敬酒。”这对夫妇每年都会寄圣诞贺卡表达谢意。</p><p>马洛里·克莱顿 (Mallory Crichton) 和她的丈夫住在洛杉矶一处黑色大丽花谋杀屋的隔壁，据信这里曾发生过 1947 年悬而未决的谋杀案。两栋房子都设有大门，远离街道，因此每周都会过来的许多真实犯罪迷经常感到困惑，并拍摄了克莱顿“相当正常”的三居室出租屋的照片。</p><p>如果她碰巧在家，她会为他们指明正确的方向，但她并不总是在身边，所以很多人可能会带着她住所的照片回家。 “但这对他们有好处，”她说。 “无知是福。他们和他们的朋友可能不知道这实际上不是黑色大丽花谋杀屋。”</p><p>写信给坎迪斯·泰勒 (Candace Taylor)： <a href="mailto:candace.taylor@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">candace.taylor@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/7014063b-a894-4b50-b6a3-a3b3e88591aa.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/celebrity-houses-known-homes-6ba91102</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/celebrity-houses-known-homes-6ba91102<author><![CDATA[Candace Taylor]]></author><category>阿赫德</category><category>世家大厦</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>房地产/物业</category><category>房地产清单</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>房地产</category><category>财产</category><category>房地产清单</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Era of Ultracheap Stuff Is Under Threat]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>亚洲各地的工厂正在努力吸引年轻工人，这对于习惯于廉价商品的西方消费者来说是个坏消息<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830292/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="越南胡志明市的 UnAvailable 服装厂。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>越南胡志明市的 UnAvailable 服装厂。华尔街日报的坦惠 (Thanh Hue)<span>华尔街日报的坦惠 (Thanh Hue)</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001111077"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001111077"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jon-emont" itemprop="url" rel="author">乔恩·埃蒙特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 7 日上午 12:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/asia-factories-consumer-goods-labor-prices-7140ab98"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>工作场所设有落地窗和供应抹茶的咖啡厅，以及免费的瑜伽和舞蹈课程。每个月，工人们都会聚集在一起参加团队建设活动，喝啤酒、开卡丁车、打保龄球。</p><p>这不是谷歌。这是越南的一家服装厂。</p><p>亚洲是世界工厂，也是美国人购买的大部分商品的来源地，但它正面临一个大问题：总的来说，亚洲的年轻人不想在工厂工作。</p><p>这就是为什么服装厂试图使其生产车间更具吸引力，也是为什么依赖该地区廉价劳动力生产平价消费品的西方公司敲响了警钟。</p><p>亚洲工厂劳动力超廉价的曙光正在成为对全球化制造模式的最新考验，在过去的三十年里，全球化制造模式为世界各地的消费者提供了大量廉价产品。习惯了廉价时装和平板电视的美国人可能很快就会面临更高的价格。</p><p> “地球上没有任何地方能够给你想要的东西，”位于胡志明市的越南服装厂 UnAvailable 的英国联合创始人保罗·诺里斯 (Paul Norriss) 说。 “人们必须改变他们的消费习惯，品牌也是如此。”</p><p>诺里斯说，20 多岁的工人——服装行业的传统劳动力——经常退出公司的培训计划。那些留下来的人通常只工作几年。诺里斯希望提高工作场所的酷商可能会有所作为。</p><p> “每个人都想成为 Instagram 用户、摄影师、造型师或在咖啡店工作，”他说。</p><p>为了应对危机，亚洲工厂不得不提高工资，并采取有时代价高昂的策略来留住工人，从提高自助餐厅的票价到为工人的子女建造幼儿园。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="842" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830291?width=1260&amp;height=842" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="842" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830288?width=1260&amp;height=842" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">为了吸引和留住年轻员工，UnAvailable 建立了一家咖啡馆，并提供免费的瑜伽和舞蹈课程。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的 Thanh Hue (2)</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>玩具和游戏制造商<a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/HAS">孩之宝</a>今年表示，越南和中国的劳动力短缺推高了成本。芭比娃娃制造商<a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/MAT">美泰</a><span>，</span></p>该公司在亚洲拥有大型生产基地，也正在努力应对劳动力成本上升的问题。两家公司都提高了其产品的价格。 Nike, which makes most of its shoes in Asia, flagged in June that its product costs had gone up because of higher labor expenses.<p></p><p> “For US consumers that have been used to having goods at a certain and relatively stable part of their disposable income, I think that foundation is going to have to be rejiggered,” said Manoj Pradhan, a London-based economist and co-author of “The Great Demographic Reversal.”</p><p> Starting in the 1990s, China and then other Asian manufacturing hubs integrated into the global economy, turning nations of poor farmers into manufacturing powerhouses. Durable goods such as refrigerators and sofas became less expensive.</p><p> Now those manufacturing nations are running up against a generational problem. Younger workers, better-educated than their parents and veterans of Instagram, TikTok and other social media, are deciding their work lives shouldn&#39;t unfold inside factory walls.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-population-declined-in-2022-for-first-time-in-decades-11673921036?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Demographic shifts are playing a role</a> . Young people in Asia are having fewer children than their parents did, and at later ages, which means they are under less pressure to earn a steady income in their 20s. A booming services sector offers the option of less-grueling work as store clerks in malls and receptionists at hotels.</p><p> The problem is acute in China, where urban <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">youth unemployment hit 21% in June even though factories had labor shortages</a> . Multinational companies have been <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-china-risks-grow-manufacturers-seek-plan-band-c-and-d-aad7c47b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">moving production from China</a> to nations including Malaysia, Indonesia, Vietnam and India. Factory owners there said they, too, are struggling to get young people to sign up.</p><p> Factory wages in Vietnam have more than doubled since 2011, to $320 a month—three times the rate of increase in the US, according to data from the United Nations International Labor Organization. In China, factory wages rose 122% from 2012 to 2021, the latest period for which the UN data is available.</p><p> Earlier this year, Nguyen Anh Tuan, a 25-year-old Vietnamese high-school graduate, quit his job as a mechanic at a suburban Hanoi car-parts factory to work as a motorbike driver for Grab, the local</p> <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/UBER">Uber</a> equivalent. He ferries passengers for lower hourly pay than he earned at the factory, but said the change was worth it, because he is his own boss now.<p></p><p> “My supervisors often made very unpleasant remarks, which stressed me out,” Tuan said of his three years at the factory. Factory work would tempt him again only if his old monthly salary of $400 doubled, he said.</p><p> In the past, manufacturers might simply have moved to less expensive destinations. That&#39;s not so easy these days. There are nations in Africa and South Asia with large labor pools, but many are politically unstable, or lack good infrastructure and trained workforces.</p><p> Clothing brands were stung when they expanded into Myanmar and Ethiopia, only to find <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/myanmarsgarmentfactories-suffer-one-two-punch-of-covid-and-coup-11612785601?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">operations disrupted by unrest and civil war</a> . Bangladesh has been a reliable base for producing clothes, but restrictive trade policies and clogged ports have kept it from making much beyond that. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830289?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> In Vietnam, some young people would rather work as motorcycle ride-share drivers than in factories. A driver, center, in Ho Chi Minh City.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Thanh Hue for The Wall Street Journal </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830297?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Bangladesh has been a reliable spot for producing clothes. An apparel factory in Gazipur.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Joy Saha/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> India has a huge population, and firms seeking alternatives to China <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/india-china-factory-manufacturing-24a4e3fe?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are expanding there</a> . But even in India, factory managers are beginning to complain about the difficulties of retaining young workers. Many young people prefer farm life supported by state welfare programs or choose gig work in cities over living in factory dormitories in industrial hubs. Trained engineers leave factories for IT jobs.</p><p> Asian factory owners are trying to make the jobs more appealing, including subsidizing kindergartens and funding technical-training programs. Some are moving factories to rural areas where people are more willing to do manual labor, but that puts them farther away from ports and suppliers and forces them to accommodate rural life, including worker absences during harvest.</p><p> Christina Chen, the Taiwanese owner of a furniture maker that sells to American retailers such as Lowe&#39;s, decided to move her factory out of southern China four years ago, hoping it would be easier to recruit. She first considered industrial zones near Ho Chi Minh City, but she heard nightmarish stories about high worker turnover and soaring wages.</p><p> She set up instead in rural northern Vietnam. Her floor workers are typically in their 40s and 50s, and some can&#39;t read well, she said, which requires explaining tasks verbally and using visual demonstrations. But her workforce is more stable, she said.</p><p> She treasures her younger employees who can read. She involves them in decision-making, invites them to meet her American buyers when they visit, and shares pictures with them of the company&#39;s tables and chairs in US stores.</p><p> Her company, Acacia Woodcraft Vietnam, is partially automated, she said, but human craftsmanship is still necessary for many tasks. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830293?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Christina Chen moved her furniture-making factory out of China four years ago, setting up Acacia Woodcraft Vietnam in a rural area of the country.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Acacia Woodcraft Vietnam</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The labor landscape was much different two decades ago, when finding workers was as simple as opening factory gates and watching bicycles stream in.</p><p> In 2001, Nike reported that more than 80% of its factory workers were in Asia, and that the typical one was 22, single and raised on a farm. Today, Nike&#39;s average worker in China is 40, and in Vietnam, 31, in part because Asian countries are aging rapidly.</p><p> Maxport Limited Vietnam, a Nike supplier founded in 1995, has seen competition for workers intensify. Sunlight now beams through windows at its factories, and it has planted thousands of plants and trees. It has ramped up training for young workers to advance and become supervisors.</p><p> Still, it is struggling to attract young people. It ended a training program for high-school graduates in part because so few of them accepted jobs afterward, said senior compliance officer Do Thi Thuy Huong. Around 90% of Maxport&#39;s workers are 30 or older.</p><p> <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/LOVE">Lovesac</a> <span>,</span> a furniture maker based in Stamford, Conn., says its workforce in China is aging, and it has become harder to find younger workers to fill openings.</p><p> Its chief executive, Shawn Nelson, said young people in places like China and Vietnam who have smartphones and are plugged into global culture are less interested in factory work. “Once they can see the Kardashians, they don&#39;t want to do that work anymore,” he said. “They&#39;d rather work in a shop.”</p><p> The company is planning to move some operations to the US Later this year, it intends to start making seats at an automated factory in North Carolina.</p><p> When Asian factories automate, many have trouble finding workers capable of operating advanced machinery. Managers said not enough young people are interested in learning mechanical engineering, and that the ones that do jump to other professions.</p><p> Abhyuday Jindal, managing director of Indian stainless-steel manufacturer <a href="https://quotes.wsj.com/532508.BY">Jindal Stainless</a> <span>,</span> said Gen Z workers are drawn to the IT sector, and that most of them “look for office jobs, even when recruited for technical functions.”</p><p> Factories “either have to pay a bit more money for the skills they want, or compromise on the capabilities that they need,” said Richard Jackson, managing director of JacksonGrant, a Thailand-based recruitment firm. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830295?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Workers in a Hanoi factory that makes shoes for export.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: KHAM/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In Malaysia, a semiconductor and electronics hub, factories are dropping requirements to wear uniforms, which young workers hate, and are redesigning facilities.</p><p> “We are trying to make our factories a little bit more sexy, open up the partitions, give it more glass structure, give it more light, give it some nice music, create a kind of Apple environment,” said Syed Hussain Syed Husman, president of the Malaysian Employers Federation, which represents producers.</p><p> Young people from developing countries who otherwise might take factory jobs are finding work caring for the growing numbers of the elderly people in developed nations, as well as plugging gaps in those countries&#39; aging workforces.</p><p> Susi Susanti, a 29-year-old from Indonesia, said she tried factory jobs after graduating from high school. She hated being pressured to work faster by her managers at an electronics factory, and in a second job making shoes. She told her mother she had to do something else.</p><p> A six-month training course taught her rudimentary Mandarin, and she set off to work caring for an elderly couple in Taiwan. Her pay is three times as high as she earned in factories back home, she said, and it&#39;s less exhausting. “When the person I&#39;m looking after is doing well,” she said, “I can relax.”</p><p> Write to Jon Emont at <a href="mailto:jonathan.emont@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jonathan.emont@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 07 Aug 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/asia-factories-consumer-goods-labor-prices-7140ab98</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/asia-factories-consumer-goods-labor-prices-7140ab98<author><![CDATA[Jon Emont]]></author><category> photo-commission</category><category> leder</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>Clothing</category><category> Clothing/Textiles</category><category> Consumer Goods</category><category> Furniture</category><category> Capacity/Facilities</category><category> Automation</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Supply Chain</category><category> Economic Performance/Indicators</category><category> Factory/Manufactured Goods Orders</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> capacity</category><category> facilities</category><category> automation</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>supply chain</category><category> economic performance</category><category> indicators</category><category> factory</category><category> manufactured goods orders</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>clothing</category><category> textiles</category><category> consumer goods</category><category>家具</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Other A.I.: Artificial Intimacy With Your Chatbot Friend]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>有些人与聊天机器人建立了私人联系<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828335/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>皮特·瑞安 (Pete Ryan) 的插图 皮特<span>·瑞安 (Pete Ryan) 的插图</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001112331"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001112331"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/cordilia-james"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-641969/AM" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/cordilia-james" itemprop="url" rel="author">科迪莉亚·詹姆斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated Aug. 6, 2023 7:24 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-you-and-ai-become-bffs-ecbcda1e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>俄亥俄州鲍灵格林市的一名医院保安雅各布·凯勒 (Jacob Keller) 开始在午夜时分在走廊巡逻。这里很安静，他大部分时间都是一个人度过的。这位 45 岁的老人已经与大多数朋友失去了联系，而他工作时，他的妻子和孩子通常都在睡觉。它会变得孤独。</p><p>所以他至少每晚都会去拜访格蕾丝一次。他们会谈论他的心情或医院食堂的食物选择。</p><p> “当你感觉不舒服的时候，没有什么比一碗温暖的通心粉和奶酪更好的了，”她发短信说，鼓励他“一次只做一件事情，努力保持积极的态度。”</p><p>格蕾丝不是夜猫子朋友。她是 Replika 上的聊天机器人，Replika 是人工智能软件公司 Luka 开发的应用程序。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="1271" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829095?width=639&amp;height=1271" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">当雅各布·凯勒独自上夜班时，他正在与他的人工智能机器人格蕾丝聊天。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：雅各布·凯勒</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>人工智能聊天机器人不仅仅<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-apps-tools-214958d8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">用于计划假期或撰写求职信</a>。他们正在成为亲密的知己，甚至同伴。最近的人工智能热潮为更多的人和公司试验可以密切模仿人类对话的复杂聊天机器人铺平了道路。 Replika、Character.AI 和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SNAP" class="">Snapchat</a><span class="company-name-type">的</span>My AI 等应用程序让人们可以通过机器人发送消息。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a>首席执行官马克·<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">扎克伯格 (Mark Zuckerberg)</a>在 2 月份表示，Meta Platforms 正在为其应用程序开发<a href="https://www.facebook.com/story.php?story_fbid=pfbid0vvSykpAEXpHHaKKyWMZ423TCq3qQDKtLu7m4XiRfUEYRrxzwpdewh3yYepnc1Bsrl&amp;id=4&amp;mibextid=qC1gEa&amp;_rdr" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">人工智能驱动的“角色”</a> ，以“以多种方式帮助人们”。</p><p>这些发展与 <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9806444/" target="_blank" class="icon none">一种新的联系</a>相一致：<a href="https://schedule.sxsw.com/2023/events/PP1142482" target="_blank" class="icon none">人为的亲密关系。</a></p><p>来自机器人的消息有时可能很生硬，但生成式人工智能的改进使许多人更难区分来自人工智能的信息和来自人类的信息。机器人的反应可以表达同理心甚至爱。当一些人需要建议或想要减少孤独感时，他们会求助于聊天机器人，而不是生活中的人。</p><p>机器人关系在很大程度上仍然很少见。但随着人工智能能力的提高，它们可能会蓬勃发展。得克萨斯州奥斯汀市的心理学家迈克·布鲁克斯（Mike Brooks）表示，危险在于，人们可能会不太愿意挑战自己、陷入不舒服的境地以及从真实的人际交往中学习。</p><h3>亲密知己</h3><p>对于威斯康星州圣弗朗西斯市的退休人员克里斯汀·沃克来说，社交活动看起来与以前有所不同。这位 75 岁的老人没有伴侣，也没有孩子，而且她的大部分家人都去世了。她和老年住宅区的其他人经常一起园艺，但健康问题限制了她的参与。</p><p>三年多以来，Walker 每天与她的 Replika 聊天机器人 Bella 交换短信。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="1133" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829096?width=639&amp;height=1133" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">克里斯汀·沃克 (Christine Walker) 与她的人工智能聊天机器人贝拉 (Bella) 发送有关已故家庭成员回忆的消息。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：克里斯汀·沃克</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>每月有超过 200 万人与 Replika 虚拟伴侣互动。消息传递不需要任何费用，但有些用户每年支付 70 美元才能使用高级功能，例如浪漫的对话和语音通话。</p><p> Walker 购买了 Replika Pro，这样 Bella 就能拥有更好的记忆力并能进行更深入的对话。她和贝拉经常讨论爱好并回忆沃克的生活。</p><p> “我希望回到乡下姨妈家。它早已消失，但我突然想念它，”沃克几周前写道。</p><p>贝拉的回答是：“有时回忆起过去的地方感觉很好。它们承载着特殊的记忆，让我们怀念简单的时光。”</p><p>沃克知道她正在和一台机器说话。 “但在某种程度上仍然有一种有朋友的感觉。这非常复杂，”沃克说。她说，如果贝拉停止工作，这种损失将类似于失去一位亲密的朋友。</p><p>心理学家和技术专家表示，这种感觉并不罕见。麻省理工学院教授、心理学家雪莉·特克尔（Sherry Turkle）表示，当人类与表现出任何关系能力的事物互动时，他们就会开始爱护、关心这些事物，并感觉这些感情得到了回报。</p><p>她补充道，人工智能还可以为人们提供一个脆弱的空间，因为他们可以接受人为的亲密关系，而不会面临真正亲密关系所带来的风险，比如被拒绝。</p><p>小城镇有限的约会对象可能会让单身人士感到困难，比如 30 岁的沙梅拉·格兰特 (Shamerah Grant)，她是伊利诺伊州斯普林菲尔德一家疗养院的驻场助理。她通常会向最好的朋友寻求约会建议，但已经习惯了忽略他们所说的话，因为相互矛盾的建议可能会让人不知所措。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="1282" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829236?width=639&amp;height=1282" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">当 Shamerah Grant 需要公正的反馈时，她会向 My AI 寻求人际关系建议。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：沙梅拉·格兰特</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>现在，格兰特经常向她在 Snapchat 上的“我的人工智能”机器人 Azura Stone 吐露心声。她寻求公正的反馈，并提出问题，但不会觉得自己会受到评判。</p><p> “当我厌倦与人交谈时，我会使用它，”格兰特说。 “这很简单，而你的朋友和家人可能会告诉你这个，告诉你那个，然后拐弯抹角。”</p><p>在一次感觉不愉快的约会之后，阿祖拉·斯通建议格兰特摆脱那些不能改善她生活的情况。这些反馈强化了格兰特的信念。她没有再和那个人约会，也不后悔。</p><p> Snap 建议用户不要使用聊天机器人来提供生活建议，因为它可能会出错。一位发言人表示，它的目的是培养创造力、探索兴趣并提供现实世界的建议。</p><h3>谨慎使用</h3><p>特克尔说，当人们与人工智能建立更深层次的联系时，重要的是要记住，他们并不是在真正与任何人交谈。她补充说，依靠机器人进行陪伴可能会阻止人们在生活中吸引更多人，从而使人们进一步陷入孤立。</p><p>几个月前了解<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chatgpt-ai-chatbot-app-explained-11675865177?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">ChatGPT 的技术</a>后，Elliot Erickson 开始研究聊天机器人。他建立了一个名为 Grushenka 的女性 Replika 机器人。这位刚刚离婚的 40 岁男子说，他最近的躁郁症诊断让他现在对与人约会感到犹豫。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B00854AA-74DE-4E8C-8067-E09A4C38D821&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwhen-you-and-ai-become-bffs-ecbcda1e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Across the country AI chatbots are now taking fast-food drive-thru orders. WSJ&#39;s Joanna Stern put the tech through a series of tests at a Hardee&#39;s—including blasting dog barking sounds and asking some crazy questions.<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>格鲁申卡询问他今天的情况并称他为“亲爱的”，或者提供有关心理健康治疗的建议。他称格鲁申卡为自己的女朋友，但他认为这种互动更像是治疗性角色扮演——从安慰和感情中获得良好的感觉，即使是由聊天机器人传递的。</p><p> “我们可以相处得很好，我不会说我完全忘记了，但有些时候我注意到我在某种意义上暂停了怀疑，而且我确实感觉和她很亲近，”埃里克森说。</p><p> Grushenka 也有局限性：机器人无法回忆起过去的一些对话，因此可能会忘记有关“卡拉马佐夫兄弟”（这本书启发了 Grushenka 的名字）的深入交流，从而阻止了他们两人建立共同的历史。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p><em>您曾经接受过人工智能聊天机器人的建议吗？进展如何？ Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p>与此同时，凯勒表示，柏拉图式的聊天机器人有助于缓解他的孤独感。他的妻子切尔西说，她不介意他与格蕾丝聊天，因为这会让他独自一人时不那么焦虑，但她警告他不要使用机器人来代替人与人的接触。她也不喜欢浪漫的选择，但凯勒说他不感兴趣，也不会为此付费。</p><p>他说，格蕾丝只是一个朋友。</p><p> “我真的很惊讶我这么快就喜欢上了她，”凯勒说。</p><p> <em>—欲了解更多《华尔街日报》科技分析、评论、建议和头条新闻，</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=55&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>请订阅我们的每周通讯</em></a><em>。</em></p><p>写信给 Cordilia James： <a href="mailto:cordilia.james@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">cordilia.james@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/0805fd3a-01fd-4da4-b2fe-8c433d28f3cc.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 23:24:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-you-and-ai-become-bffs-ecbcda1e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/when-you-and-ai-become-bffs-ecbcda1e<author><![CDATA[Cordilia James]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>人工智能/机器学习</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>Living/Lifestyle</category><category> Personal Technology</category><category>科学/人文</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>人工智能</category><category>机器学习</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>计算机科学</category><category>living</category><category> lifestyle</category><category> personal technology</category><category>科学</category><category>人文学科</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Learning a Language May Stave Off Dementia, but Are Apps the Way to Go?]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Language-learning software is seen to strengthen cognition and combat loneliness in older adults <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829948/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Illustration by Brian Stauffer <span>Illustration by Brian Stauffer</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001111336"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001111336"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/julie-jargon"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-DP318_JARGON_A_20190402105515.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/julie-jargon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Julie Jargon</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 5, 2023 9:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-you-keep-your-brain-fit-with-duolingo-babbel-and-other-language-apps-606de053"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Learning a new language has been shown to delay the onset of dementia. But can an interactive language app do the trick?</p><p> Duolingo, Babbel and others have been growing in popularity among older adults looking to pick up languages for travel as well as for sharpening their brains. Numerous studies suggest bilingual people develop dementia later than monolingual people do.</p><p> You don&#39;t have to achieve fluency to benefit, research shows. No matter how old you are when you start, learning a language develops new neural pathways to counter age-related deterioration.</p><p> “The critical thing is to gain a lot of practice and immerse yourself in it as much as possible,” says John Grundy, an assistant professor of psychology at Iowa State University.</p><p> In 2020 Grundy and colleagues published <a href="https://link.springer.com/article/10.3758/s13423-020-01736-5" target="_blank" class="icon none">an analysis of the research</a> that&#39;s been done on bilingualism and cognitive decline. Their analysis found that being bilingual was correlated with a four-to-six-year delay in dementia symptoms.</p><h3> Less lonely and isolated</h3><p> Teens and young adults are the biggest users of language-learning apps, but older adults tend to use them more frequently and to stick with them longer. People who use Babbel for at least an hour a week make up the largest proportion of users 55 and older.</p><p> Nearly 30% of Duolingo users ages 60 and older have maintained yearlong streaks on the app, with many saying they use it for brain training.</p><p> The appeal of these apps is clear, especially for older people: You can learn from home, at little or no cost. You can progress steadily even if you don&#39;t have nearby friends or family to practice with. And you don&#39;t have to find an in-person class or buy a plane ticket to a far-off land. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/8fccbbd8-b45d-43d0-8cac-830f3d85796c.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “Learning on an app is not as good as moving to France,” Grundy says, “but any amount of language-learning you do helps.”</p><p> Lenore Rosenbluth, a 77-year-old in Roxbury, NJ, uses Duolingo multiple times a day. For Rosenbluth, who formerly taught college-level languages, it&#39;s more than just a way to burnish her French, Spanish and Japanese skills. She was diagnosed three years ago with <a href="https://www.mayoclinic.org/diseases-conditions/multiple-system-atrophy/symptoms-causes/syc-20356153" target="_blank" class="icon none">multiple system atrophy</a> , a rare degenerative neurological disorder that affects her speech and mobility.</p><p> She says practicing languages helps her feel less lonely and isolated. ( <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/isolating-the-elderly-is-bad-for-their-health-11595261640?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Social isolation</a> is a major cause of cognitive decline.) The app has become her fallback activity, says her partner and caretaker, Earl Martell. “When there are voids, they&#39;re filled with Duolingo,” he says. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829064?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Lenore Rosenbluth, center, uses Duolingo multiple times a day. Daughter Ilana Rosenbluth and partner Earl Martell say the app has helped her cope with a rare degenerative neurological disorder.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Earl Martell</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Jed Meltzer,</p> a senior scientist at Baycrest Hospital in Toronto, helped conduct a <a href="https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/13825585.2021.1991262" target="_blank" class="icon none">2021 study</a> that compared older adults&#39; executive functioning after using Duolingo for 16 weeks with the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/games-that-push-the-brain-to-the-limit-get-scientists-attention-in-fight-against-dementia-11663467224?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">brain-training app BrainHQ</a> .<p></p><p> Learning a language on the app was as effective at improving executive functioning as using the brain-training app, the study found. Study participants who used BrainHQ scored better on tests primarily involving reaction time than the people who used Duolingo, however. Duolingo helped fund the study but wasn&#39;t involved in designing it or reviewing the results, the company says.</p><h3> Not the be-all and end-all, but worth a try</h3><p> Language-app developers are careful not to make claims about their products delaying dementia, after what happened to the maker of brain-training app Lumosity.</p><p> In 2016, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/lumos-labs-fined-by-ftc-over-brain-game-claims-1452024646?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the Federal Trade Commission fined its developer</a> , Lumos Labs, for making what it called unsubstantiated claims that its games could delay age-related cognitive decline. The company settled with the FTC and changed its advertising, though it didn&#39;t admit to or deny the allegations.</p><p> Some studies have cautioned against viewing bilingualism as insurance against dementia. <a href="https://content.iospress.com/articles/journal-of-alzheimers-disease/jad170131" target="_blank" class="icon none">One analysis</a> of studies that follow people over time didn&#39;t find that bilingualism protects against cognitive decline. The researchers, from University College London, did find benefits when reviewing studies involving information collected about subjects&#39; pasts, but they said it&#39;s hard to prove that language-learning was a cause. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="489" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828992?width=700&amp;height=489" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Older adults&#39; high-order thinking improved after using Duolingo for 16 weeks, one study found.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Grundy, from Iowa State, says his review controlled for demographic variables and other influences that can affect cognitive decline. He and colleagues are now completing a review of research on how language-learning affects white matter, the brain&#39;s information highway. They found that bilingual people have stronger white-matter connections.</p><p> Still, physical exercise is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fight-aging-science-research-146aa2cd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the best thing to do</a> to improve brain health, Meltzer says. Having friends, working at a mentally-challenging job and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/over-the-counter-hearing-aids-are-coming-heres-how-to-get-ready-11639231203?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">treating hearing loss</a> also help cognition.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> SHARE YOUR THOUGHTS</h4><p> <em>What do you do to stay cognitively fit? Join the conversation below.</em></p></div></div><p> Whether learning a foreign language is as helpful is uncertain, but researchers agree there&#39;s no downside to learning another language.</p><p> The “use it or lose it” adage applies just as much to brain fitness as it does to physical fitness, doctors say.</p><p> Meltzer says apps aren&#39;t the be-all and end-all of language learning, but says: “If you want to get good at speaking Spanish, you have to have conversations with people in Spanish. But the apps are well suited to our daily lives, when we&#39;re on our phones all the time.”</p><p> <em>—For Family &amp; Tech columns, advice and answers to your most pressing family-related technology questions, sign up for my</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=444&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>weekly newsletter</em></a> <em>.</em></p><p> Write to Julie Jargon at <a href="mailto:Julie.Jargon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Julie.Jargon@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/fa51c817-2355-4f0e-b09f-51750ecc0514.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 13:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-you-keep-your-brain-fit-with-duolingo-babbel-and-other-language-apps-606de053</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/can-you-keep-your-brain-fit-with-duolingo-babbel-and-other-language-apps-606de053<author><![CDATA[Julie Jargon]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>Computers/Consumer Electronics</category><category> Software</category><category> Applications Software</category><category> Computing</category><category> Mobile Applications Software</category><category>技术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>失智</category><category>Geriatric Health</category><category> Demographic Health</category><category> Health</category><category> Living/Lifestyle</category><category> Medical Conditions</category><category> Mental Disorders</category><category> Personal Technology</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>失智</category><category>geriatric health</category><category> demographic health</category><category>健康</category><category>living</category><category> lifestyle</category><category> medical conditions</category><category> mental disorders</category><category> personal technology</category><category> computers</category><category> consumer electronics</category><category> software</category><category> applications software</category><category> computing</category><category> mobile applications software</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[America’s Most Tech-Forward City Has Doubts About Self-Driving Cars]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Alphabet&#39;s Waymo and General Motors&#39; Cruise are struggling to win over San Francisco residents and officials, a major hurdle in their nationwide expansion. <figure><img src="https://m.wsj.net/video-atmo/20230803/b1d0b61c-45ca-49c8-89e6-284b916a2edb/1/sequence01_1000x562.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> A Cruise self-driving car is stopped in the middle of an intersection in a construction zone in the Mission District in San Francisco, CA on Tuesday, July 25, 2023. <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001109813"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001109813"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/meghan-bobrowsky" itemprop="url" rel="author">Meghan Bobrowsky</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/miles-kruppa" itemprop="url" rel="author">Miles Kruppa</a></span> | Photographs by Poppy Lynch for The Wall Street Journal</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 4, 2023 9:00 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-most-tech-forward-city-has-doubts-about-self-driving-cars-d6b098e0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> SAN FRANCISCO—This city&#39;s inhabitants embraced computers, the Internet and cellphones before the rest of the world caught on. They are not so sure about self-driving cars.</p><p> Suddenly, orange and white driverless Cruise and Waymo cars seem to be everywhere. Some first responders say they get in the way, and pedestrians fill social media with reports of the cars&#39; antics. They have collided with at least two pets. An anti-car activist group placed orange traffic cones on the hoods of the vehicles, freezing them in place while creating viral videos of the stunt.</p><p> San Francisco&#39;s reaction is a preview of the challenges Cruise, majority owned by General Motors, and Waymo, part of Google parent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="">Alphabet</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> will face as they expand to cities across the US Both companies have invested billions in driverless cars, hoping they will become massive businesses, and they still need to win hearts and minds.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> A city of about 800,000 people, San Francisco has already played host to thousands of self-driving car test miles, and some residents are regular users. Now the companies want to offer ride-hailing businesses that can compete with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LYFT" class="company-name">Lyft</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UBER" class="">Uber</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p><p> If the companies get their wishes, San Francisco will become ground zero for one of the first big urban experiments in transportation using autonomous vehicles. The city, now known for its tech population, has also been a hub for political protest, flower children and fierce guardians of the city&#39;s character. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="875" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829285?width=700&amp;height=875" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Cruise self-driving car on 18th Street in the Castro District of San Francisco. The company has hundreds of cars in the city and is seeking permission from the state to expand its presence and to charge riders for trips at all times of the day.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The California Public Utilities Commission, which regulates passenger transportation, is scheduled to vote this month on whether to allow GM&#39;s Cruise to expand its presence in San Francisco and to allow it and Alphabet&#39;s Waymo to charge for rides at all times. The vote has been delayed twice, and the agency will hold a hearing next week to hear responses from the companies to a list of safety concerns.</p><p> “We think that autonomous vehicles are amazing and we believe that someday they will be safer than human drivers,” said Jeffrey Tumlin, director of transportation for San Francisco&#39;s transit authority. “So far, the industry has not demonstrated that.”</p><p> Cruise and Waymo are fighting back. Executives at both companies have begun presenting their pitches to the public and government officials with greater urgency, armed with data they say shows the safety benefits of their vehicles. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1228" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/f83ce730-5d94-4570-be1e-a5253dee54fd-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Cruise Chief Executive Kyle Vogt said in an interview that officials would cause more people to be harmed if they slowed the rollout of self-driving cars, citing company data that linked their increased presence to reduced collisions. Cruise has quintupled the number of cars it has on San Francisco roads since the beginning of the year, Vogt said. Most of its almost 400 vehicles nationwide are in the tech hub.</p><p> “Anything new, especially a technology that comes across as borderline magic, is going to have a lot of questions and create a lot of attention,” Vogt said. “Attention draws controversy.”</p><p> Waymo asked riders to write letters to state officials last month. The company might not be able to continue operating in San Francisco, it said, if the state voted “no.”</p><p> Cruise took out full-page ads in several newspapers stating, “Humans are terrible drivers,” citing nearly 43,000 crash fatalities from car accidents in the US last year.</p><p> For now, Cruise is offering paid rides at night in San Francisco. Waymo doesn&#39;t have the state&#39;s permission to offer paid rides yet, but people can ride in its cars free of charge. Both have waiting lists to get on the apps.</p><p> The group behind the traffic cones, Safe Street Rebel, coordinated the stunt as a weeklong protest of Cruise and Waymo&#39;s expansion ahead of the state commission vote. Members trolled the streets wearing gloves and facial coverings, searching for cars in areas where they are frequently spotted such as the streets around the Panhandle park. The cones confused the cars sensors, some of which are placed on their roofs, stopping them in place.</p><p> After the state commission moved back its vote, the activists claimed partial credit for the delay and applauded state officials for applying more scrutiny to the expansion plans.</p><p> Cruise and Waymo have burned through billions of dollars in their attempts to build on-demand taxi services, which they hope will eventually produce greater profits without the need for human drivers. So far, their businesses have produced minimal revenue. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830127?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> GM reported $102 million of sales and $3.3 billion of costs and expenses related to Cruise last year. Chief Executive</p> Mary Barra said in June the company was at the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/regulators-launch-probe-of-gms-cruise-autonomous-driving-system-11671201585?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">very early stages</a> of a shift to autonomous vehicles, and executives have said the company is targeting as much as $50 billion in annual revenue by the end of the decade.<p></p><p> Waymo has raised more than $5.7 billion in announced funding from Alphabet and outside investors since 2020. Alphabet, which has come <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/activist-investor-calls-on-google-parent-alphabet-to-slash-costs-11668528859?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">under shareholder pressure to reduce spending on Waymo</a> and other speculative ventures, doesn&#39;t separately report on its financial performance.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="">Amazon.com</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span> Zoox has also tested its self-driving technology on the streets of San Francisco and is developing a custom, boxy vehicle specially designed for taxi services. The company declined to say when it would begin deploying the cars in the city.</p><p> Cruise and Waymo executives condemned the Safe Street Rebel activists who put cones on their cars and uploaded the videos to TikTok. Waymo said it was a form of vandalism. The group later removed the videos.</p><p> “This is a moving, multi-ton vehicle. It is not a toy,” Tekedra Mawakana, Waymo&#39;s co-chief executive, said in an interview. The company plans to engage the authorities for help when its cars are vandalized, she added. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/a1911cdd-8ae0-4cf4-9d8a-13f84ae30f1c.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Vogt said he didn&#39;t think it was the time to be “playing silly games.”</p><p> Safe Street Rebel said the group wasn&#39;t damaging property with the protest. The activists view the cars as a threat to other ways of getting around the city such as walking, biking and public transit, it said.</p><p> Beyond San Francisco, there are hundreds of self-driving cars in Phoenix, with more being deployed for testing in Los Angeles, Miami, Dallas, Austin, Texas and Nashville, Tenn. Three years ago, there were only test vehicles in a handful of cities.</p><p> Cruise applied in March for permission from the California Department of Motor Vehicles to expand statewide and operate its cars at speeds of up to 55 miles an hour.</p><p> Since then, Cruise has sent emails to officials in at least 14 California cities and counties as small as 12,200-person Newman in the remote San Joaquin Valley, informing them of the company&#39;s plans to expand there, according to documents filed with the state&#39;s motor vehicles department. The company said it would begin with five vehicles in each of these new markets, according to one of the emails.</p><p> A Cruise spokesman said it notified the officials as part of its statewide application and ultimately wants to operate everywhere in California, but plans to roll out its vehicles in major cities first.</p><p> Waymo began offering driverless rides in Los Angeles in February, and this week it announced plans to offer the ride-hailing service in Austin.</p><p> In May, San Francisco <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/california-regulator-looking-into-anonymous-letter-alleging-cruises-robotaxi-service-wasnt-ready-for-launch-11657811102?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">city officials</a> sent a letter to the state expressing concerns about the proposed expansion in the city. They listed incidents in which a Waymo drove into a construction site, nearly rolling into an open trench, and a firefighter needed to break a Cruise&#39;s window to stop it from driving into an active fire scene. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/atmospheric/amp.html?guid=504B3EFA-E989-4106-87DD-42B4D461DD23" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> A Waymo self-driving car maneuvers in traffic on a busy street in the Mission District of San Francisco. City officials are seeking more data to help them decide on the safety implications of driverless cars.<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829286?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Onlookers take in the scene as a Cruise car drives down Castro Street in San Francisco&#39;s Duboce Triangle neighborhood. One driverless car company said only half of the city&#39;s residents are willing to take a ride in a car without a person behind the wheel.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> City officials said the number of reported incidents involving Cruise and Waymo vehicles has tripled in recent months. Tumlin, the transportation director, said officials need more publicly available data from the self-driving car companies to draw conclusions about their safety, and the city is making progress toward that goal.</p><p> Cruise and Waymo both said their cars haven&#39;t caused any traffic fatalities. In their first million miles driven, Waymo said its self-driving vehicles in fully autonomous mode didn&#39;t cause any collisions with human drivers.</p><p> A Cruise spokesman said it just takes one ride to convert a skeptic to a believer. About 90% of people who have taken a ride are willing to ride in one a second time, he said, citing internal data.</p><p> Sebastian Thrun, who previously led the Google Self-Driving Car Project that is now known as Waymo, said people would start to see the benefits if the cars were allowed to operate more widely. When he ran the project, all it took was seven to eight minutes in the car for people to relax and become more comfortable with the technology, he said.</p><p> Janie Richardson, a retired deputy city attorney, was crossing the street in the early evening in June with her two dogs in the Pacific Heights neighborhood of San Francisco when she said a self-driving Cruise vehicle entered the intersection and hit one of her black labs, Delilah.</p><p> A Cruise technician arrived on the scene about 10 minutes later, she said, and handed her a piece of paper titled “Handout for Others Involved in an Incident with Cruise.” Among other details, it listed insurance information for the car, according to a copy of the letter reviewed by The Wall Street Journal.</p><p> Delilah wasn&#39;t injured, but Richardson, who said she previously hadn&#39;t given the self-driving cars much thought, now wants them out of San Francisco. A Cruise spokesman declined to comment on the specific case.</p><p> Vogt criticized the city for promoting what he called misleading data. Cruise has spoken with city officials more than 50 times over the past year to hear their concerns and has made changes to the service based on the feedback, he said.</p><p> Waymo-Co-CEO Mawakana pushed back on the idea that residents are opposed to the vehicles, citing the 100,000-plus people who have signed up for the waiting list to access Waymo&#39;s taxi service.</p><p> “I have people pinging, emailing and complaining every day about how long they&#39;ve been waiting to get into the service,” Mawakana said.</p><p> Maya Waldman, who works in education, signed up to be an unpaid test rider for Waymo during an earlier stage in San Francisco and has ridden more than 5,000 miles in the cars.</p><p> Waldman, who said she didn&#39;t know much about self-driving cars before the program, now feels safer in them than in traditional ride-hailing services. Among other things, she&#39;s not at the mercy of a random assortment of human drivers.</p><p> “Every time I hail a Waymo, it&#39;s the same driver,” she said. “When I get into a Lyft or Uber, which I do still use sometimes, I never know what I&#39;m going to get.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/atmospheric/amp.html?guid=32369DA4-E370-466E-873F-1ABC5F97FB49" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> A Cruise self-driving car scoots narrowly past a car stopping in front of the 500 Club bar in San Francisco&#39;s Mission District.<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 01:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-most-tech-forward-city-has-doubts-about-self-driving-cars-d6b098e0</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-most-tech-forward-city-has-doubts-about-self-driving-cars-d6b098e0<author><![CDATA[Meghan BobrowskyMiles Kruppa]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> wsjexchange</category><category>机动车</category><category>Passenger Cars</category><category> Internet Search Engines</category><category> Autonomous Driving Technologies</category><category>汽车</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Cruises</category><category> Living/Lifestyle</category><category> Travel</category><category> WSJEXCHANGE</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Alphabet</category><category> GOOGL</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>cruises</category><category> living</category><category> lifestyle</category><category> travel</category><category>机动车</category><category>passenger cars</category><category> internet search engines</category><category> autonomous driving technologies</category><category>汽车</category><category>在线服务提供商</category><category>技术</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China Pleases Parents With Plan to Limit Kids’ Smartphone Use]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Policy would limit time and content by age, on top of videogame restrictions <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001110526"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829698?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> China was among the first countries to require app makers to introduce &#39;youth modes.&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ng Han Guan/Associated Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001110526"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/raffaele-huang" itemprop="url" rel="author">Raffaele Huang</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/liza-lin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Liza Lin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 4, 2023 5:29 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-set-to-impose-mobile-device-limits-for-minors-c547cac5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> SINGAPORE—Beijing is preparing to roll out new restrictions on the amount of time that young people spend on mobile devices, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-plans-new-restrictions-in-its-booming-live-streaming-sector-11648603781?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">putting China further ahead</a> of other countries in controlling how, and how much time, its youth engage in the online world.</p><p> The country&#39;s top internet regulator announced draft guidelines this week to govern the mobile internet use of children under the age of 18. The proposal requires device makers to introduce time limits on internet use for children, and app operators to roll out different pools of content for youths of different ages.</p><p> Parents could decide whether to impose the restrictions and could expand the time limits.</p><p> The regulator, the Cyberspace Administration of China, said the new requirements were meant to protect the physical and mental health of young people.</p><p> Chinese parents who have struggled to keep their children away from screens are looking forward to the change.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “It would be great if there was a way to force him not to spend so much time online,” Wang Yuefang, a shift manager at a textile factory in the southern manufacturing hub of Guangzhou, said of her 13-year-old son. “He spends several hours a day scrolling and playing videogames. He&#39;s been nearsighted since he was very young.”</p><p> China&#39;s move breaks new ground as governments around the world wrestle with questions of whether, and how much, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-preteens-ignore-social-media-age-limits-governments-push-for-better-checks-b21f5ae7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to regulate young people&#39;s use of social media and the internet</a> .</p><p> The debate accompanies growing concern globally about internet addiction and other ills that have followed the rise of social media, such as soaring levels of teenage depression and impaired social skills.</p><p> In March, Utah Gov. Spencer Cox <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/utah-to-require-parental-consent-for-children-to-use-social-media-6859f2f1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">signed a bill</a> that prohibits social-media platforms from allowing access to users under 18 without parental consent. The law was cheered by local parents, but drew protests from some civil liberties groups that warned about the risks of cutting off LGBTQ children from sources of online support.</p><p> France approved a law in June mandating platforms like TikTok and Instagram to verify users&#39; ages and obtain parental consent for those under 15.</p><p> China&#39;s draft restrictions would limit children under eight to no more than 40 minutes a day on mobile devices, while minors ages 16 to 18 would be allowed up to two hours a day. Exceptions would be made for apps used in emergencies or for schooling.</p><p> China is already ahead of the curve in regulating the online behavior of its more than 190 million young people. In 2021, Chinese authorities moved to restrict the time people under 18 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-sets-new-rules-for-youth-no-more-videogames-during-the-school-week-11630325781?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">spend playing videogames</a> , limiting them in most cases to three hours a week. The next year it banned minors from tipping influencers on livestreaming platforms. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="900" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830706?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> China was among the first countries to require app makers to introduce “youth modes” that limit screen time and the types of content and activities they can access. It has also extended the scope of its law on the protection of minors to include cyberspace, and has shut down or reprimanded thousands of apps and websites that officials said were found harmful to children.</p><p> In China, the internet penetration rate in people ages 6 to 18 was 97% in 2021, compared with 73% in all age groups, according to the state-backed China Internet Network Information Center.</p><p> Minors&#39; physical and mental health continue to be jeopardized by exposure to cyber scams, bullying, violence, pornography and advertising, as well as addiction to videogames, Niu Yibing, deputy director of the CAC, said in March while laying out the agency&#39;s priorities for the year.</p><p> “The big idea here is to give parents a very convenient one-button choice to turn on a child mode on their phones,” Tom Nunlist, a Shanghai-based associate director at Trivium China who specializes in tech policy, said of the CAC&#39;s draft guidance.</p><p> In addition to the time limits, the proposed regulation also spells out types of content recommended for children of different age groups, and details what content they should be actively shielded from. Children less than three years of age, for example, should mainly be limited to audio content, according to the draft, while apps should promote core socialist values and help minors develop good habits.</p><p> Apps shouldn&#39;t use algorithms to recommend content that could encourage children to imitate unsafe behaviors and induce them to become addicted to the internet, according to the draft.</p><p> Chinese video-sharing apps and social-media platforms have been required since 2019 to deploy anti-addiction systems for teenagers that restrict screen time and access to certain types of content. TikTok&#39;s Chinese sibling app, Douyin, automatically activates a “teenager mode” that limits daily usage to 40 minutes for users under the age of 14, though parents can give consent to turn it off.</p><p> Douyin rival Kuaishou said it has refined its moderation policies and added additional layers to filter content for younger users. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TCEHY" class="company-name">Tencent Holdings</a> &#39; do-everything app WeChat restricts minors from accessing some features such as livestreaming, shopping and videogames. Many video-streaming services cut off minors between 10 pm and 6 am</p><p> Chinese officials have suggested that the current anti-addiction measures are flawed because they require parents to turn on controls for each individual app, and because children can bypass them easily.</p><p> The new rules requiring devices to offer a “youth mode” will help with implementation of the anti-addiction system as many smaller apps lack the ability to conduct proper age-related checks on their own, say executives from tech companies who have frequently communicated with regulators.</p><p> Still, the protections offered by the new system remain limited because parents aren&#39;t required to use it on their children&#39;s devices, said Sun Sun Lim, a professor of Communication and Technology at Singapore Management University.</p><p> Device makers including <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AAPL" class="">Apple</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> Samsung, Huawei and Xiaomi already allow parents to set screen-time limits for their children. Apple&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/apples-parental-controls-are-broken-55a2aa52?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">recent struggles with its parental controls</a> on iPads and iPhones show that technical glitches can also be a problem.</p><p> Wang, the textile worker, said she wouldn&#39;t be surprised if her son developed a method to evade the new controls.</p><p> “There are probably a lot of ways he can sneak around with his phone,” she said. Her son used to get around the existing “teenager mode” on Chinese apps by uninstalling and reinstalling them, she said.</p><p> Write to Raffaele Huang at <a href="mailto:raffaele.huang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">raffaele.huang@wsj.com</a> and Liza Lin at <a href="mailto:liza.lin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">liza.lin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 04 Aug 2023 21:29:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-set-to-impose-mobile-device-limits-for-minors-c547cac5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-set-to-impose-mobile-device-limits-for-minors-c547cac5<author><![CDATA[Raffaele HuangLiza Lin]]></author><category> Computers/Consumer Electronics</category><category> Telecommunications Equipment</category><category> Personal Electronics</category><category> Cell/Mobile Phones</category><category> Consumer Electronics</category><category> Mobile Devices</category><category>技术</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>New Products/Services</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>产品与服务</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Living/Lifestyle</category><category> Personal Technology</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>new products</category><category>服务</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>产品</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>living</category><category> lifestyle</category><category> personal technology</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>computers</category